<div><h3>MSPC 3224 - Socio-Digital Engineering </h3>  <p><hr>This course centers on one idea: Code is not neutral. This maxim represents a paradigm to</p>

<p>understand how &#8220;Online&#8230;our lived experience of &#8216;ever-increasing&#8217; pervasiveness of information.</p>

<p>and communication technologies,&#8221; (Floridi) when left unexamined, may have inherent.</p>

<p>consequences of which we should not remain ignorant. Medium Theory provides a theoretical</p>

<p>backdrop to understand socio-political phenomena such as the Arab Spring to Arab Winter and</p>

<p>political change in Tunisia in the context of digital communications, while disruptive</p>

<p>technologies, e.g., blockchain, IoT, AI, virtual reality are also put under this critical lens. By</p>

<p>exploring the Attention Economy, robots and AI, and individual privacy within public spaces</p>

<p>students will develop an understanding of how digital communications technologies themselves.</p>

<p>can construct our reality. The central importance of digital ethics in business contexts via</p>

<p>corporate social responsibility efforts are also examined.<br><br><strong>Anticipated Terms Offered:</strong> Varied<br><br></p></div>		</td>
